So for light userdata, it explicitly returns "light userdata" as a special case, rather than using the standard type name from `TYPE_NAMES`.

Our Rust `obj_type_name` function doesn't handle this distinction—it only checks for metatables on tables and userdata, so light userdata falls through and returns "userdata" instead of "light userdata". I need to add a specific case for `LuaValue::LightUserData` to return the correct string. But this also means the error messages would need to use `obj_type_name` instead of `type_name()` to get the right behavior.

